That's a lot of rice, throw a little lettuce in there to balance it out! It's okay. Spices are okay not super impressed but it eats well. I'm used to getting a small 1/4 to 1/2 cup sized salad in these kinds of dishes but this one was all rice, some meat, some chickpeas. I get that you need to preserve profit in this covid life we're living but let's be reasonable here. I ordered kabob with rice not rice with kabob.

It used to be really good (about 3 yrs ago). Not sure why the quality and quantity started going down. However, it is one of the very few places where I would order a biryani from (In DC). Other places do NOT match up to the flavor that Red Toque offers. That being said, I sincerely hope they would go back to what they were doing back in 2016. It was really good!
Nah
Chicken Korma was flavorless, garlic naan too, korma didn’t have enough sauce to cover the rice. Very disappointed!

Amazing food. Definitely worth the money. Only reason giving 4 stars is, there is some smell inside for dine-in. If they work a bit on their ambience, it’ll be 5/5!!  I guess you could give 4.5 for pickup food.
Phenomenal food, great staff and friendly service. A must dine experience in DC.

The food is delicious, though I think the portions could be a little larger. I get either the butter chicken or chicken tikka masala. Their both the same, except the tikka masala has like pepper and other veggies. Love it.

I’ll say it. DC’s best Indian! I’ll admit, it’s probably because it’s Indian/Pakistani. I’ve tried the Butter Chicken and Chicken Tikka Masala... both dense in flavor and layered. Not watery at all. Love that they always include chana masala (chick peas. The beef Samosas are a must try. The highlight though are the vegetable pakoras... the best I’ve ever had. My only wish is that they had some beef curries (Nehari maybe). To date the only place I’ve found with beef curries was in Texas, but one can hope.

I got a lamb kabob with the spinach curry side. The lamb was magnificent, but it was laid simply on a bed of unseasoned rice. Mixing in the spinach curry was the saving grace. Next time I'll try one of the biriyanis so I get seasoned rice with the dish.
Outstanding. Will order for delivery again. Super quick and good quality.

I was just here and the cashier was so rude. He told me not to touch the salad that i was about to pay for so i left salad because the way he said dont shake it that was so rude and then he did not gave my money in my hand that was his rude behaviour.. i will never come back here again 👎

If you're looking for a quick Indian bite, this is the place. Had Chicken Biryani and Baklava cake. Amazing for money I paid and the quantity they served. One biryani was good for 2 people. Recommended for those sudden Indian food cravings if you're in the vicinity

I will not be visiting this restaurant again, and would caution others against it as well. I got the curry, which consisted of a small bowl of oil, with a tiny amount of meat "juice" with a few specks of dried out meat. There was no spice in any of the dishes whatsoever, and I'm not sure if we're feeling queasy from the oil or if the food was off.

Taste was awful, portions small ($13 = 5 scraps of meat for a kabob), and price was way too high. I said I was going to give this 2-stars unless it made us sick. Now waiting to see if the food was just so full of oil that we feel sick, or it actually made us sick.

I searched for this cafe over the net and wasn't sure when i reached there but the taste really blew us. We ordered chicken biryani and chicken karahi along with fresh roti. I must say one of the best karahi we had in US and biryani really taste good. The cafe itself is small and is owned by a couple, whose wife is Pakistani/Indian and the cook is from Bangladesh. The roti bread was fresh is like what you find in Karachi Pakistan. The owner itself looks after guest and is friendly. If you are in town and urging for a good karahi, drop in and enjoy.

This meal was so disappointing that I can't even comprehend the positive reviews.   I ordered through UberEATS and chose this restaurant because of its high rating.  I ordered lamb chops, chicken vindaloo, spinach and chickpeas.  The lamb was dry and mealy and super salty.  The vindaloo had no heat whatsoever (vindaloo should be fiery hot), and the chicken was dry (how do you get chicken in a stew to be dry?   Seems impossible) and the vegetables tasted of nothing but salt and cardamom.  Even the baclava managed to be dry and was undercooked.  $70 for a wholly inedible meal.    Bummer.

I was happy with my food but annoyed that the amount charged on my card was wrong. I ordered the chicken kebab plate while eating here last night. The food was average, the chicken was well done and was good quality chicken. The service was decent, the waiter didn't know much english but he was quick with refilling our drinks. There are two prices for the kebab plates, one is a small and a full plate. Apparently these mean lunch and dinner sizes. So small = lunch and full = dinner. When it came to paying the wait was very long. I was afraid that the amount that would be charge would be wrong and I was right. I should have paid around $16, but they charged my card about $24. It's not a huge deal but annoying. I will not be coming back.

I live around the corner and have patronized Red Toque for a couple years now.  The food has always been very worth the fair price.  The service has always been friendly but often incorrect or slow.  I highly recommend it!
I was near this restaurant for work and decided to stop in.  It was delicious, definitely the best I have eaten.

I love this place. I work nearby, so it's a regular go to spot for lunch. (I joke that I don't look forward to having kids because then I won't be able to justify going here for lunch so often!)  The Chicken Karahi is excellent. Get it with their fresh-baked naan. The Lamb Biryani is my default dish. The Tandori chicken is great -- comes with a side, too. The Chicken Curry is especially good when there -- the curry comes in a pan so you can enjoy the sauce before it soaks into the rice.  The owner is a great partner in conversation. He's always willing to talk politics and world affairs I'm always happy to engage him. I love this place (and I've gotten half a dozen of my colleagues to fall in love with it too.)  Note: the orders do take a little longer to prepare then at some places. But I gave it a very good because they seem to remember how you like it and make it that way for you. So it pays to be a regular. And I know most of it is cooked-to-order. When it comes to things like naan, that is worth the wait! (I just call as I'm leaving the office so it's ready or near-ready by the time I'm there.)
